\f0\b\fs44 \cf0 Directions\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\sa140\ql\qnatural

\f1\b0\fs42 \cf0 Mix the ground meats, ricotta, parsley, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/panko/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 panko}} crumbs, onion, pecorino, bacon, garlic, milk, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/thyme/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 thyme}}, egg, salt, Worcestershire, and black pepper, to taste, in a large bowl. Mix until just combined; don't overmix. The mixture will be pretty soft.\
Using your hands, gently form mixture into 1 tablespoon small meatballs (about the size of ping pong balls). Put them on a large plate or pan; cover and refrigerate at least an hour or up to 24 hours.\
Heat the oil in a medium nonstick skillet over medium-high heat. Add about 1/3 the meatballs and cook, turning occasionally, until well browned on all sides, about 6 minutes. Transfer the meatballs to a plate and repeat with the remaining meatballs.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\sa140\ql\qnatural
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/drain/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Drain}} off the oil and wipe out the skillet. Return the meatballs to the skillet and pour in the marinara sauce. Bring to a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/boil/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 boil}}, lower the heat, cover, and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/simmer/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 simmer}} until the meatballs are cooked through, about 15 minutes.\
Serve the meatballs, skewered on a platter with a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/dollop/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 dollop}} of the sauce and a fresh leaf of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/basil/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 basil}}. They can be serve warm or at room temperature.\
The meatballs can be stored, covered, in the refrigerator for 3 days, or frozen for up to 6 weeks.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl320\ql\qnatural

\f0\b\fs44 \cf0 Meatball wisdom:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\sa140\ql\qnatural

\f1\b0\fs42 \cf0 - Be gentle when you're forming meatballs--too firm a hand makes them dense and tough.\
- These can be frozen cooked (in sauce) or raw; freeze raw meatballs on a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/cookie/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 cookie}} sheet, then transfer them to resealable plastic bags. Cooked-in-sauce meatballs can go into plastic containers.\
